1 NEW SECTION. Section 3. Central registry -- hearing -- appeal. (1) Prior to the adjudication
2 hearing, the department shall provide the individual with the full investigative file and any exculpatory evidence
3 within the department's possession or control in accordance with 41-3-205.
4 (2) Discovery prior to the hearing must be conducted in accordance with Title 25, chapter 20, and
5 41-3-431. Following the adjudication hearing, if the district court finds that there is a preponderance of the
6 evidence supporting the department's substantiation determination, the substantiated allegations against the
7 individual may be added to the central registry for a period of time determined by the court, not to exceed 25
8 years and proportionate to:
9 (a) the severity of the act of child abuse or neglect; and
10 (b) the risk of threat or harm to children that the individual poses.
11 (3) If the district court finds that there is insufficient evidence supporting the department's
12 determination, the court shall order the department to amend its findings accordingly and the allegation may not
13 be added to the central registry.
14 (4) The individual has a right to appeal the decision of the district court regarding placement on the
15 central registry.
